I have a version that I've been using for years.  It's older but it has all of the functionality of the newer versions but does not support some of the newer adapters.  Tell me what adapters you have (or will be using) and I'll tell you if they will work with this version.  

Moreover, if you don't have a compatible adapter you can but one of the top rated adapters for less than $20 on eBay.  It's a TP-Link adapter.  I have two that I use, the TP-Link TL-WN821N (USB) and an Enterasys Networks PCMCIA Dual Band Client Card (Atheros Chipset) model number RBTBJ-AW, it uses the old dual band setup.  802.11 a/b/g - 2.4GHz/5GHz of course.

Both of these were under $20 I believe.  So let me know what adapters you have and we'll go from there.  

With ANY compatible (well, a recommended compatible adapter) you'll be "cracking" WEP keys in no time! 

And stick with Aircrack-NG for Win.  It's your best bet and works just fine for me despite all of the bad reviews.  Cain and Able is a great tool, but for what you want to do I seriously suggest that you stick with Commview for WiFi and Aircrack-NG.

Unfortunately, for WPA/WPA2 I would not recommend Commview.  I would recommend using Pyrit, and if you have a powerful graphics card then you will be able to premutate PMK's faster, much faster.  You can also use mySQL rather than the "stock" db application Pyrit uses and turn a few old workstations into Pyrit clients all dedicated to "cracking" WPA/WPA2 keys. 

In other words, you setup a Pyrit server and you can setup Pyrit clients to share their resources towards your cause.  (Or not, lol!  You can just use a single workstation or laptop).  Moreover, you can use a laptop to go out and capture packets and then copy them over to your pyrit box (must be in .pcap format) instead of hoping your adapter's range is going to extend to where you want it to from your workstation.

Pyrit does not work with AES encrypted keys but does for PSK and TKIP for sure. 

By the way, Pyrit can only be used on Linux right now.  I recommend Ubuntu 11.04 (not 11.10) using the old Gnome Desktop Environment and disabling Unity but nearly any Linux distro will work aside from the "Pendrive Versions".

The link aggregator server receives the packet, splits it into many pieces, and delivers each piece evenly across the fake clients to the Raspberry Pi, where it is recombined, and delivered through the AP to the client. ok, so here is a very basic mod you can do to a flash drive to make it hidden, for easy installs of your sever.

what you need:
  a flash drive with a case that is easy to remove.
  solder / solder iron.
  very thin wire (i used 30 ga. warping wire)
  hot glue.

ok, so first putt the flash drive apart and wiggle the usb plug until it pops off, NOTE THE WAY YOU SET IT DOWN!!! ( i recommend putting a sharpie dot on the right of the circuit and the right of the plug, so you know what what the correct way is.

cut 4 equal pieces of wire. the smaller the better. now solder the connection points back together. if you don't know how... just give up... the contacts are very close together.

after they are all soldered, add a dab of glue to hold it together then coil the wire.

[img]http://www.upload.ee/image/1829446/make-it-ra1n.jpg[/img]

[IMG]http://www.yadabn.com.np/web_images/install-cydia-with-limera1n-e1286662831207.png[/IMG]

Hi there guys.

Just finished reading the American journalist/nonfiction type novel, In Cold Blood, by Truman Capote. And boy, all I could say at the end was "wow."

The book gives you the creeps and leaves room for suspense throughout the book.

Here's an excerpt from Wikipedia:

***QUOTE***Quote:In Cold Blood is a non-fiction book first published in 1966, written by American author Truman Capote; it details the 1959 murders of Herbert Clutter, a farmer from Holcomb, Kansas, his wife, and two of their four children.

When Capote learned of the quadruple murder, before the killers were captured, he decided to travel to Kansas and write about the crime. He was accompanied by his childhood friend and fellow author Harper Lee, and together they interviewed local residents and investigators assigned to the case and took thousands of pages of notes. The killers, Richard "Dick" Hickock and Perry Smith, were arrested six weeks after the murders, and Capote ultimately spent six years working on the book.

The book is the second biggest selling true crime book in publishing history, behind Vincent Bugliosi's 1974 book Helter Skelter on the Manson murders.

Some critics consider Capote's work the original non-fiction novel, although other writers had already explored the genre, such as Rodolfo Walsh in Operación Masacre (1957). The book examines the complex psychological relationship between two parolees who together commit a mass murder. Capote's book also explores the lives of the victims and the effect of the crime on the community in which they lived. In Cold Blood is regarded by critics as a pioneering work of the true crime genre, though Capote was disappointed that the book failed to win the Pulitzer Prize.[1]

Parts of the book, including important details, differ from the real events.***QUOTE***

Definitely check it out guys. The murder scene is really gruesome and makes you feel really bad.
